1
00:00:04,771 --> 00:00:06,139
Hello, Mum.

2
00:00:06,607 --> 00:00:08,809
Susie says hello. Don't you, sweetheart?

3
00:00:08,909 --> 00:00:12,646
(GASPING) That's it. Give a little wave.

4
00:00:12,746 --> 00:00:15,449
(CHUCKLING) What was I gonna say?

5
00:00:15,916 --> 00:00:18,619
Uncle Soon called in. He says hello.

6
00:00:19,586 --> 00:00:22,055
He keeps saying,
"You must be missing her."”

7
00:00:22,389 --> 00:00:27,227
I said, "She's been gone for over
two years now. I'm getting used to it.”

8
00:00:28,028 --> 00:00:32,332
(DISTORTED) [It's breaking up.
It must be the solar flares.

9
00:00:32,399 --> 00:00:33,534
Talk faster.

10
00:00:34,001 --> 00:00:35,702
About the deposit on the house, I've...

11
00:00:35,802 --> 00:00:36,837
(BABY CRYING)

12
00:00:36,937 --> 00:00:39,373
Oh. Um... I've spoken to the bank...

13
00:00:43,310 --> 00:00:45,345
(WHOOSHING)

14
00:00:52,252 --> 00:00:53,487
DOCTOR: The red planet.

15
00:01:08,468 --> 00:01:10,370
(ALARM BLARING)

16
00:01:12,506 --> 00:01:13,974
(ALARM STOPS)

17
00:01:15,909 --> 00:01:18,011
ED ON RADIO: Sun sets
in 19 minutes, Yuri.

18
00:01:18,111 --> 00:01:19,279
You're gonna lose the light.

19
00:01:20,047 --> 00:01:23,650
MIA: That's it. Got you on external 10.

20
00:01:25,752 --> 00:01:26,920
YURI: Almost there.

21
00:01:28,755 --> 00:01:31,124
That's the radial clamp down.

22
00:01:31,892 --> 00:01:32,960
One more thing...

23
00:01:33,160 --> 00:01:36,563
Get back inside.
You're using power and oxygen.

24
00:01:36,663 --> 00:01:40,267
Oh, hold on. Get this on camera.

25
00:01:40,367 --> 00:01:41,401
(LAUGHING)

26
00:01:41,702 --> 00:01:42,803
What do you think?

27
00:01:42,903 --> 00:01:45,472
Hey, looks good. Nice one, Yuri.

28
00:01:45,572 --> 00:01:48,508
You wasted an entire solar panel
just to make that.

29
00:01:48,609 --> 00:01:51,345
Oh, lighten up. It's a joke.

30
00:01:51,445 --> 00:01:55,182
We come all this way to an empty planet
untouched by civilisation

31
00:01:55,282 --> 00:01:58,385
and what do we do? Put up cheap jokes.

32
00:01:58,485 --> 00:02:00,887
That's not funny, that's pollution.

33
00:02:01,355 --> 00:02:03,323
-Having fun?
-I was just telling him...

34
00:02:03,423 --> 00:02:06,593
I expect better of you, Ed.
Now get back to work, all of you.

35
00:02:17,404 --> 00:02:19,172
Oh, beautiful.

36
00:02:25,412 --> 00:02:29,249
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Rotate, slowly.

37
00:02:29,349 --> 00:02:33,720
You are under arrest for trespassing.
Gadget-gadget.

38
00:02:39,059 --> 00:02:41,328
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

39
00:03:19,499 --> 00:03:21,635
State your name, rank and intention.

40
00:03:21,802 --> 00:03:25,672
The Doctor. Doctor...Fun.

41
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:28,608
What the hell?

42
00:03:30,444 --> 00:03:31,712
It's a man!

43
00:03:32,479 --> 00:03:34,881
Man on Mars. How?

44
00:03:34,981 --> 00:03:38,285
He was wearing this thing.
I have never seen anything like it.

45
00:03:38,385 --> 00:03:39,486
What did Mission Control say?

46
00:03:39,586 --> 00:03:41,722
They're out of range for 10 hours
with the solar flares.

47
00:03:41,822 --> 00:03:43,123
If you could cut the chat, everyone.

48
00:03:43,223 --> 00:03:47,527
Actually, chat's second on my list,
the first being gun pointed at my head.

49
00:03:48,295 --> 00:03:50,597
Which then puts my head second
and chat third, I think.

50
00:03:50,697 --> 00:03:52,499
Gun, head, chat. Yeah. I hate lists.

51
00:03:52,599 --> 00:03:55,202
But you could hurt someone
with that thing. Just put it down.

52
00:03:55,302 --> 00:03:56,770
Oh, you'd like that.

53
00:03:56,870 --> 00:03:58,705
Can you find me someone who wouldn't?

54
00:03:58,805 --> 00:04:02,175
-Why should I trust you?
-Because I give you my word.

55
00:04:02,476 --> 00:04:06,880
At 40 million miles away from home,
my word is all you've got.

56
00:04:11,184 --> 00:04:12,385
Keep Gadget covering him.

57
00:04:12,486 --> 00:04:13,553
Gadget-gadget.

58
00:04:13,653 --> 00:04:16,656
Oh right, so you control that thing.
Auto-glove response.

59
00:04:16,757 --> 00:04:18,658
You got it. To the right.

60
00:04:19,426 --> 00:04:22,195
-Gadget-gadget.
-And to the left.

61
00:04:22,429 --> 00:04:23,864
It's a bit flimsy.

62
00:04:24,564 --> 00:04:25,565
Gadget-gadget.

63
00:04:25,665 --> 00:04:26,800
Does it have to keep saying that?

64
00:04:26,900 --> 00:04:28,034
I think it's funny.

65
00:04:28,135 --> 00:04:29,503
I hate funny robots.

66
00:04:29,603 --> 00:04:34,508
Excuse me, boss. Computer log says
we've got an extra person on site.

67
00:04:34,674 --> 00:04:36,009
How's that possible?

68
00:04:36,109 --> 00:04:40,547
Keep the Bio-dome closed. And when using
open comms, you call me Captain.

69
00:04:41,348 --> 00:04:43,383
Yeah, but who is it?

70
00:04:44,284 --> 00:04:45,619
(RADIO DISCONNECTING)

71
00:04:47,387 --> 00:04:50,524
Disconnected! She's cut me off.
Can you believe her?

72
00:04:51,024 --> 00:04:53,293
It's like we're just gardeners.

73
00:04:53,693 --> 00:04:57,030
As long as they leave us alone,
it's fine with me.

74
00:05:00,433 --> 00:05:03,837
Oh, you beauties.

75
00:05:04,137 --> 00:05:05,472
Look at this.

76
00:05:06,306 --> 00:05:09,543
Better start planting some more
if there's an extra mouth to feed.

77
00:05:09,643 --> 00:05:14,181
The very first garden off Earth.
Everything brand new.

78
00:05:15,682 --> 00:05:19,452
Eden. That's what we should have
called this place.

79
00:05:19,853 --> 00:05:22,289
It's the Philippines, I bet.

80
00:05:22,389 --> 00:05:25,192
If there's someone else on Mars,
it's got to be the Philippines.

81
00:05:25,292 --> 00:05:27,994
All those stories about them
building a rocket.

82
00:05:28,094 --> 00:05:33,033
(SCOFFING) Adelaide is gonna love that.
Stealing her thunder.

83
00:05:33,633 --> 00:05:36,269
Mind you, worth it to see her face.

84
00:05:36,369 --> 00:05:38,038
Or it could be the Spanish.

85
00:05:38,138 --> 00:05:41,041
They've kept that space link project
under wraps.

86
00:05:41,508 --> 00:05:43,376
Didn't your sister work for them?

87
00:05:45,912 --> 00:05:47,514
Are you all right, mate?

88
00:05:50,250 --> 00:05:52,986
(CHUCKLING) Come on, stop mucking about.

89
00:05:57,224 --> 00:05:58,391
Andy?

90
00:06:01,828 --> 00:06:03,263
Are you okay?

91
00:06:05,665 --> 00:06:07,868
(SCREAMING)

92
00:06:11,037 --> 00:06:13,006
It can't be a World State flight
because we'd know about it.

93
00:06:13,106 --> 00:06:15,775
Therefore he's got to be one
of the independents, yeah?

94
00:06:16,877 --> 00:06:18,879
Was it the Branson Inheritance lot?

95
00:06:18,979 --> 00:06:20,547
They've been talking
about a Mars shot for years.

96
00:06:20,647 --> 00:06:24,517
Right, yes. Okay, you got me.
So, I'm the Doctor and you are?

97
00:06:24,618 --> 00:06:28,288
Oh, come on. We're the first
off-world colonists in history.

98
00:06:28,388 --> 00:06:30,757
Everyone on planet Earth
knows who we are.

99
00:06:31,358 --> 00:06:35,896
You're the first?
The very first humans on Mars?

100
00:06:36,429 --> 00:06:38,732
-Then this is Bowie Base One.
-Bowie Base One.

101
00:06:39,099 --> 00:06:42,135
Number One. Founded July 1st, 2058.

102
00:06:42,235 --> 00:06:45,071
Established Bowie Base One
in the Gusev Crater.

103
00:06:51,344 --> 00:06:54,347
-You've been here how long?
-Seventeen months.

104
00:06:54,748 --> 00:06:55,982
20597

105
00:06:57,951 --> 00:06:59,853
It's 2059 right now.

106
00:07:03,623 --> 00:07:04,891
(EXCLAIMING)

107
00:07:04,991 --> 00:07:09,195
My head is so stupid.
You're Captain Adelaide Brooke!

108
00:07:12,365 --> 00:07:14,935
And Ed, you're Deputy Edward Gold.

109
00:07:18,204 --> 00:07:19,706
Tarak Ital, MD.

110
00:07:23,910 --> 00:07:25,445
Nurse Yuri Kerenski.

111
00:07:29,716 --> 00:07:31,584
Senior technician Stef ft Ehrlich.

112
00:07:33,753 --> 00:07:35,422
Junior technician Roman Groom.

113
00:07:38,091 --> 00:07:39,693
Geologist Mia Bennett.

114
00:07:42,262 --> 00:07:43,763
You're only 27 years old.

115
00:07:45,031 --> 00:07:48,468
As I said, Doctor,
everyone knows our names.

116
00:07:48,568 --> 00:07:50,870
Oh, they'll never forget them.

117
00:07:56,309 --> 00:07:57,811
What's the date today?

118
00:07:58,211 --> 00:07:59,846
What is it? Tell me the exact date.

119
00:08:00,046 --> 00:08:03,083
November 21st, 2059.

120
00:08:07,253 --> 00:08:10,824
Right. Okay, fine.

121
00:08:10,924 --> 00:08:12,559
Is there something wrong?

122
00:08:12,659 --> 00:08:14,694
What's so important about my age?

123
00:08:15,061 --> 00:08:16,930
I should go.

124
00:08:18,064 --> 00:08:20,500
I really should go. I'm sorry.

125
00:08:20,934 --> 00:08:23,903
(STAMMERING) I'm sorry
with all of my hearts,

126
00:08:24,004 --> 00:08:27,974
but it's one of those very rare times
when I've got no choice.

127
00:08:32,445 --> 00:08:34,347
It's been an honour.

128
00:08:35,615 --> 00:08:39,986
Seriously, a very great honour
to meet you all.

129
00:08:41,121 --> 00:08:43,223
The Martian pioneers.

130
00:08:44,257 --> 00:08:46,726
Oh, thank you. Ah!

131
00:08:47,494 --> 00:08:48,661
Gadget-gadget.

132
00:08:49,629 --> 00:08:50,764
Thank you.

133
00:08:54,100 --> 00:08:59,239
There's the other two. Hold on.
Margaret Cain and Andrew Stone.

134
00:09:07,213 --> 00:09:11,051
Maggie, if you want to meet
the only new human being

135
00:09:11,151 --> 00:09:13,920
that you're gonna see
in the next five years,

136
00:09:14,020 --> 00:09:15,321
better come take a look.

137
00:09:17,090 --> 00:09:18,725
(SNARLING)

138
00:09:22,062 --> 00:09:23,096
What was that?

139
00:09:24,064 --> 00:09:26,132
Oh, I really should go.

140
00:09:26,900 --> 00:09:29,169
This is Central.
Bio-dome, report immediately.

141
00:09:29,269 --> 00:09:30,537
Show me the Bio-dome.

142
00:09:34,174 --> 00:09:35,675
Internal cameras are down.

143
00:09:35,775 --> 00:09:37,177
Show me the exterior.

144
00:09:48,655 --> 00:09:49,856
I'm going over.

145
00:09:50,557 --> 00:09:52,025
Doctor, with me.

146
00:09:52,692 --> 00:09:56,396
I'm sorry. I'd love to help,
but I'm leaving right now.

147
00:09:56,496 --> 00:09:58,031
Take his spacesuit, lock it up.

148
00:09:58,131 --> 00:10:00,900
This started as soon as you arrived,
so you're not going anywhere,

149
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,302
except with me.

150
00:10:11,077 --> 00:10:12,412
Gadget-gadget.

151
00:10:12,946 --> 00:10:14,514
ADELAIDE: What's so important
about Mia's age?

152
00:10:14,614 --> 00:10:17,350
You said she's only 27.
Why does it matter? What did you mean?

153
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:19,586
Oh, I just open my mouth
and words come out.

154
00:10:19,686 --> 00:10:22,188
-They don't make much sense.
-You're telling me.

155
00:10:22,288 --> 00:10:25,191
-Thank you, Doctor.
-Anytime, Doctor.

156
00:10:25,291 --> 00:10:26,826
Gadget-gadget.

157
00:10:27,093 --> 00:10:28,862
I hate robots, did I say?

158
00:10:28,962 --> 00:10:32,632
Yeah, and he's not too fond of you.
What's wrong with robots?

159
00:10:32,732 --> 00:10:35,001
It's not the robots, it's the people.

160
00:10:35,101 --> 00:10:36,402
Dressing them up
and giving them silly voices,

161
00:10:36,503 --> 00:10:37,904
like you're reducing them.

162
00:10:38,004 --> 00:10:41,875
Yeah. A friend of mine, she made
her domestic robot look like a dog.

163
00:10:42,075 --> 00:10:44,878
Oh, well, dogs, that's different.

164
00:10:44,978 --> 00:10:48,982
But I adapted Gadget out of the worker
drones. Those things are huge.

165
00:10:49,082 --> 00:10:51,184
They built this place when the shell
was lowered down from orbit.

166
00:10:51,284 --> 00:10:53,353
They've got a strength capacity
of 15 tonnes...

167
00:10:53,453 --> 00:10:56,823
The channel is open
for essential communications only.

168
00:10:58,525 --> 00:10:59,559
Sorry.

169
00:11:00,927 --> 00:11:02,395
Love those drones.

170
00:11:03,163 --> 00:11:06,232
I've read all that stuff about you,
Captain Adelaide.

171
00:11:06,332 --> 00:11:09,836
One thing they never said,
was it worth it, the mission?

172
00:11:10,236 --> 00:11:12,639
We've got excellent results
from the soil analysis.

173
00:11:12,739 --> 00:11:14,574
I know... But all of it.

174
00:11:15,441 --> 00:11:18,044
They say you sacrificed everything,

175
00:11:18,478 --> 00:11:21,014
devoted your whole life to get here.

176
00:11:22,982 --> 00:11:24,817
It's been chaos back home.

177
00:11:24,918 --> 00:11:30,123
Forty long years, climate,
the ozone, the oil apocalypse.

178
00:11:31,658 --> 00:11:33,459
We almost reached extinction.

179
00:11:34,727 --> 00:11:36,563
And to fly above that,

180
00:11:37,530 --> 00:11:40,433
to stand on a world with no smoke,

181
00:11:40,533 --> 00:11:43,503
where the only straight line
is the sunlight,

182
00:11:45,772 --> 00:11:48,775
-yes, it's worth it.
-Ah.

183
00:11:49,475 --> 00:11:52,378
That's the Adelaide Brooke
I always wanted to meet.

184
00:11:52,478 --> 00:11:55,114
The woman with starlight in her soul.

185
00:11:58,051 --> 00:11:59,219
What's that?

186
00:12:01,688 --> 00:12:02,889
-It's Maggie.
-Don't touch her!

187
00:12:02,989 --> 00:12:07,927
I know the procedure. Maggie,
can you hear me? It's Tarak. Maggie?

188
00:12:08,995 --> 00:12:12,398
It's okay. She's still breathing.
She's alive.

189
00:12:16,169 --> 00:12:19,472
Yuri, I've got Margaret Cain,
head trauma. I need a full med pack.

190
00:12:20,006 --> 00:12:22,375
I've got it. Med pack on its way.

191
00:12:22,809 --> 00:12:23,910
I'm going to help!

192
00:12:24,010 --> 00:12:25,979
In the absence of the Captain,
you're in charge, sir!

193
00:12:26,079 --> 00:12:28,248
You've got to stay in the dome!

194
00:12:37,924 --> 00:12:39,359
Don't touch her. Use the gloves.

195
00:12:39,459 --> 00:12:43,830
Do what he says. Get her to sickbay.
Put her in isolation.

196
00:12:44,130 --> 00:12:45,498
We're going on to the Bio-dome.

197
00:12:45,598 --> 00:12:48,268
Tarak, with me.
Yuri can take care of her. Ed, go back.

198
00:12:48,368 --> 00:12:50,470
Gadget, stand guard.
Keep an eye on this area.

199
00:12:50,570 --> 00:12:51,738
Gadget-gadget.

200
00:12:51,838 --> 00:12:52,972
Captain, you're gonna need me.

201
00:12:53,072 --> 00:12:55,174
Andy is the only other
crew member out here.

202
00:12:55,275 --> 00:12:59,579
And if that wasn't an accident,
then he's gone wild.

203
00:13:00,213 --> 00:13:02,715
You've deserted your post.
Consider that an official warning.

204
00:13:02,815 --> 00:13:05,151
Now, get back to work. Doctor!

205
00:13:08,855 --> 00:13:10,356
(SNARLING)

206
00:13:20,667 --> 00:13:23,536
Captain, that sound we heard
from the Bio-dome,

207
00:13:23,636 --> 00:13:27,373
I've run it through diagnostics.
According to the computer, it's Andy.

208
00:13:28,174 --> 00:13:31,210
It registers as the voice print
of Andy Stone.

209
00:13:31,511 --> 00:13:34,647
Understood. Double-check, thanks.

210
00:13:35,048 --> 00:13:36,849
Air pressure stabilised.

211
00:13:36,949 --> 00:13:38,584
(DOOR OPENING)

212
00:13:43,289 --> 00:13:47,360
Andrew? Andrew Stone?
It's Captain Brooke.

213
00:13:48,728 --> 00:13:51,497
Andrew, report. I need to see you.
Where are you?

214
00:13:51,597 --> 00:13:53,399
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

215
00:13:55,335 --> 00:13:56,669
DOCTOR: There you go.

216
00:13:57,437 --> 00:13:59,839
-What's that device?
-Screwdriver.

217
00:14:00,073 --> 00:14:04,077
-Are you the Doctor or the janitor?
-I don't know. It sounds like me.

218
00:14:04,410 --> 00:14:06,145
The maintenance man of the universe.

219
00:14:06,245 --> 00:14:08,314
You, stay with me.
Don't step out of my sight.

220
00:14:08,414 --> 00:14:10,917
Tarak, go to external door south.
Make sure it's intact.

221
00:14:10,983 --> 00:14:12,018
Yes, ma'am.

222
00:14:12,118 --> 00:14:16,122
Quite an achievement.
First flower on Mars in 10,000 years.

223
00:14:17,623 --> 00:14:18,891
And you're growing veg!

224
00:14:18,991 --> 00:14:21,594
It's that lot. They're already
planning Christmas dinner.

225
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:25,365
Last year it was dehydrated protein.
This year they want the real thing.

226
00:14:25,598 --> 00:14:29,802
-Still, fair enough. Christmas.
-If we must.

227
00:14:30,269 --> 00:14:32,038
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

228
00:14:33,206 --> 00:14:35,775
-You've got birds!
-It's part of the project,

229
00:14:35,875 --> 00:14:37,910
to keep the insect population down.

230
00:14:38,010 --> 00:14:40,713
-Good sign.
-In what way?

231
00:14:41,013 --> 00:14:42,682
Well, they're still alive.

232
00:14:42,782 --> 00:14:47,186
Captain, good news. It's Maggie.
She's awake. She's back with us.

233
00:14:47,520 --> 00:14:49,389
(GROANING)

234
00:14:50,356 --> 00:14:54,927
Hey, how are you, soldier?
Just take it easy.

235
00:14:55,161 --> 00:14:56,629
Can you remember what happened?

236
00:14:57,864 --> 00:15:00,767
I was just working.

237
00:15:01,968 --> 00:15:03,269
Then I woke up here.

238
00:15:03,803 --> 00:15:07,006
What about Andy? We can't find him.
Was he all right?

239
00:15:07,407 --> 00:15:09,208
I don't know. I just...

240
00:15:09,709 --> 00:15:12,178
ADELAIDE: If you remember anything,
let me know straightaway.

241
00:15:12,278 --> 00:15:14,180
Yuri, does she know
how she ended up in the tunnel?

242
00:15:14,280 --> 00:15:17,550
And keep the comms clear.
Everything goes through me, got that?

243
00:15:18,451 --> 00:15:19,619
(SIGHING)

244
00:15:20,153 --> 00:15:25,224
Come on, just let me out of here.
I'm fine. Just groggy.

245
00:15:25,324 --> 00:15:28,261
You know the rules. 24 hours.

246
00:15:33,266 --> 00:15:34,667
TARAK: Andy?

247
00:15:36,169 --> 00:15:39,038
Andy? Andy?

248
00:15:41,641 --> 00:15:42,809
(WATER RUNNING)

249
00:15:43,242 --> 00:15:44,310
There you are.

250
00:15:47,280 --> 00:15:48,514
You all right?

251
00:15:53,986 --> 00:15:55,121
Andy?

252
00:16:02,528 --> 00:16:03,696
Andrew,

253
00:16:04,630 --> 00:16:05,998
look at me.

254
00:16:06,232 --> 00:16:07,200
(SHOUTING)

255
00:16:08,835 --> 00:16:12,472
(SPEAKING RUSSIAN)

256
00:16:13,840 --> 00:16:15,641
Is that your brother?

257
00:16:15,842 --> 00:16:19,378
Well, it's only a repeat.
The solar flares are still up.

258
00:16:20,246 --> 00:16:24,484
-Are you okay?
-Yeah. Just, you know.

259
00:16:29,188 --> 00:16:32,225
(LAUGHING) He makes me laugh, though.

260
00:16:32,325 --> 00:16:35,561
It's his husband.
He spends money like an idiot.

261
00:16:35,695 --> 00:16:39,665
Last year for Mikhail's birthday,
he said, "Don't buy me anything.

262
00:16:39,765 --> 00:16:41,501
"Let's save money."

263
00:16:41,601 --> 00:16:43,936
George says, "Fine, okay."

264
00:16:44,036 --> 00:16:47,907
His birthday comes around,
turns out George has bought him a car,

265
00:16:48,541 --> 00:16:50,176
top of the range.

266
00:16:51,277 --> 00:16:54,380
And the thing is
he's used Mikhail's credit stamp.

267
00:16:54,480 --> 00:16:56,849
So Mick's saying,
"That means I bought it myself."

268
00:16:56,949 --> 00:16:59,886
George says,
"It's the thought that counts.”

269
00:17:01,954 --> 00:17:05,057
-Where does he live?
-Oh, just outside Dagestan.

270
00:17:05,758 --> 00:17:08,895
-Where's that?
-On the Caspian Sea. Here you go.

271
00:17:11,264 --> 00:17:14,467
-By the sea?
-Well, technically, it's more of a lake.

272
00:17:16,068 --> 00:17:19,539
-Earth is so much water.
-Yeah.

273
00:17:20,139 --> 00:17:23,543
Just look at her. 40 million miles away.

274
00:17:23,876 --> 00:17:26,112
MAGGIE: It has so much beauty.

275
00:17:27,179 --> 00:17:30,082
(DISTORTED VOICE)
We should like that world.

276
00:17:37,456 --> 00:17:41,527
This is sickbay. We have a situation.
Maggie's condition is...

277
00:17:41,627 --> 00:17:44,263
(STAMMERING) I don't know...
I don't know what it is.

278
00:17:44,497 --> 00:17:46,933
It's water, just pouring out.

279
00:17:47,266 --> 00:17:50,036
ADELAIDE: Yuri, calm down.
Just tell me what's happened to her.

280
00:17:50,136 --> 00:17:53,406
The skin is sort of broken
around the mouth.

281
00:17:53,506 --> 00:17:56,876
And she is exuding water,
like she's drowning.

282
00:17:57,310 --> 00:18:00,179
Tarak, this area's unsafe.
We're going back.

283
00:18:01,581 --> 00:18:02,748
Tarak?

284
00:18:04,550 --> 00:18:06,552
-Tarak!
-Where was he?

285
00:18:10,423 --> 00:18:13,693
Yuri, keep her contained.
Seal the door at maximum. I'm on my way.

286
00:18:27,640 --> 00:18:30,343
Andy, just leave him alone.

287
00:18:30,876 --> 00:18:33,179
-Step away from him.
-I can help, I promise. I can help.

288
00:18:33,279 --> 00:18:34,380
Just leave that man alone.

289
00:18:34,480 --> 00:18:36,549
Andy, I'm asking you,
please just take your hand away from him

290
00:18:36,649 --> 00:18:38,150
-and listen to me.
-Stop or I'll shoot.

291
00:18:49,629 --> 00:18:53,299
There now, that's better, hmm?

292
00:18:55,468 --> 00:18:59,538
So, you must be Andy. Hello.

293
00:19:06,145 --> 00:19:07,747
We've got to go.

294
00:19:30,369 --> 00:19:32,171
DOCTOR: Set the seals at maximum!

295
00:20:07,139 --> 00:20:08,607
What the hell?

296
00:20:11,777 --> 00:20:14,914
That's not Maggie.
What's happened to her?

297
00:20:15,014 --> 00:20:17,616
Yuri, what is she?

298
00:20:18,250 --> 00:20:19,885
Captain, we need you back here.

299
00:20:19,985 --> 00:20:22,888
Just tell me that Maggie is contained.
Can you confirm, Ed?

300
00:20:23,489 --> 00:20:24,590
Confirmed.

301
00:20:25,858 --> 00:20:27,359
She's locked in.

302
00:20:27,460 --> 00:20:30,963
Keep surveillance till I get back
and close down all water supplies.

303
00:20:31,063 --> 00:20:33,365
All pipes and outlets.
Don't consume anything.

304
00:20:33,466 --> 00:20:35,468
Have you got that, everyone?
That's an order.

305
00:20:35,568 --> 00:20:39,939
Don't drink the water.
Don't even touch it. Not one drop.

306
00:20:42,708 --> 00:20:44,176
Can you talk?

307
00:20:46,378 --> 00:20:49,982
Human beings are 60% water,
which makes them the perfect host.

308
00:20:50,049 --> 00:20:51,617
What for?

309
00:20:51,884 --> 00:20:57,022
I don't know.
I never will...because I've got to go.

310
00:20:58,524 --> 00:21:02,495
Whatever started here,
I can't see it to the end. I can't.

311
00:21:03,763 --> 00:21:04,864
(GASPING)

312
00:21:05,831 --> 00:21:07,166
(SNARLING)

313
00:21:09,268 --> 00:21:11,604
-This thing's airtight, yeah?
-And, therefore, watertight.

314
00:21:11,704 --> 00:21:13,205
Depends how clever the water is.

315
00:21:14,807 --> 00:21:18,043
-They're fusing the system.
-Abandon ship!

316
00:21:42,735 --> 00:21:43,803
Doctor, we haven't got time.

317
00:21:43,903 --> 00:21:45,938
They can run faster than us.
We need a lift.

318
00:21:46,739 --> 00:21:47,807
Hey!

319
00:21:48,140 --> 00:21:49,642
Gadget-gadget.

320
00:21:50,910 --> 00:21:52,645
(SCREAMING)

321
00:21:56,982 --> 00:21:59,084
-Get on behind me.
-That thing goes at two miles an hour.

322
00:21:59,185 --> 00:22:01,086
Not any more. Trust me.

323
00:22:02,922 --> 00:22:04,690
-Gadget-gadget.
-DOCTOR: Gadget-gadget.

324
00:22:05,558 --> 00:22:06,926
(SCREAMING)

325
00:22:34,253 --> 00:22:36,655
The central dome airlocks have got
Hardinger seals.

326
00:22:36,755 --> 00:22:37,857
There's no way they can get in.

327
00:22:37,957 --> 00:22:39,124
-DOCTOR: Come on! Come on!
-Gadget-gadget.

328
00:22:39,225 --> 00:22:40,226
Come on, come on, come on!

329
00:22:40,326 --> 00:22:42,127
-I thought you hated robots.
-I do!

330
00:22:52,805 --> 00:22:55,774
We're safe. It's hermetically sealed.
They can't get in.

331
00:22:57,042 --> 00:23:00,946
Water is patient, Adelaide.
Water just waits.

332
00:23:01,547 --> 00:23:06,085
It wears down the cliff tops,
the mountains, the whole of the world.

333
00:23:06,585 --> 00:23:08,487
Water always wins. Come on.

334
00:23:09,421 --> 00:23:10,789
ADELAIDE ON RADIO: Bio-dome tunnel
ls out of bounds.

335
00:23:10,890 --> 00:23:13,158
Andy and Tarak are infected,
repeat, infected.

336
00:23:13,259 --> 00:23:15,895
Make no contact. And if they make
the slightest move, tell me.

337
00:23:15,995 --> 00:23:17,363
I'm going to the Medical dome.

338
00:23:18,297 --> 00:23:20,566
(BEEPING)

339
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:24,837
Blimey, it's the distance.
You could do with bikes in this place.

340
00:23:24,937 --> 00:23:27,373
Every pound in weight equals
three tonnes of fuel.

341
00:23:27,473 --> 00:23:30,609
Yeah, I know, but bikes...

342
00:23:41,553 --> 00:23:44,924
-Has that door got a Hardinger seal?
-No, just basic.

343
00:23:45,024 --> 00:23:47,426
Then the moment she heads for the door,
we evacuate, got that?

344
00:23:47,526 --> 00:23:51,063
Pulse is low. Electrical activity
in the brain seems to be going haywire.

345
00:23:51,163 --> 00:23:52,498
-Can she talk?
-YURI: Don't know.

346
00:23:52,598 --> 00:23:55,000
She was talking
before we noticed the change, but...

347
00:23:55,100 --> 00:23:57,770
Maggie, can you hear me?
Do you know who I am?

348
00:23:58,404 --> 00:24:01,040
Your commanding officer
Captain Adelaide Brooke.

349
00:24:01,140 --> 00:24:02,675
Can you tell me what happened?

350
00:24:02,775 --> 00:24:05,377
(SPEAKING ALIEN LANGUAGE)

351
00:24:08,480 --> 00:24:09,615
What language is that?

352
00:24:09,715 --> 00:24:11,283
Ancient North Martian.

353
00:24:11,517 --> 00:24:14,053
-Don't be ridiculous.
-It's like she recognised it.

354
00:24:14,253 --> 00:24:16,355
And her eyes are different.

355
00:24:16,822 --> 00:24:19,591
They're clear,
like she's closer to human.

356
00:24:20,125 --> 00:24:21,727
Not close enough for me.

357
00:24:23,162 --> 00:24:25,631
-Where do you get your water from?
-The ice field.

358
00:24:25,731 --> 00:24:28,734
That's why we chose the crater.
We're on top of an underground glacier.

359
00:24:29,301 --> 00:24:30,436
Tonnes of water. Marvellous.

360
00:24:30,536 --> 00:24:34,106
But every single drop is filtered.
It's screened, it's safe.

361
00:24:34,206 --> 00:24:35,808
Looks like it, yeah.

362
00:24:36,041 --> 00:24:38,410
If something was frozen down there,

363
00:24:38,510 --> 00:24:41,880
a viral life form out in the ice
for all those years...

364
00:24:42,514 --> 00:24:46,218
Look at her mouth. All blackened
like there's some sort of fission.

365
00:24:47,753 --> 00:24:53,192
This thing, whatever it is, doesn't just
hide in water, it creates water.

366
00:24:56,161 --> 00:24:57,830
Tell me what you want.

367
00:24:58,197 --> 00:25:01,133
She was looking at the screen, at Earth.

368
00:25:01,333 --> 00:25:05,371
She wanted Earth. A world full of water.

369
00:25:05,971 --> 00:25:07,639
Captain, with me.

370
00:25:12,511 --> 00:25:15,047
I'm sorry, but it's an unknown infection
and it's spreading.

371
00:25:15,147 --> 00:25:16,982
That demands Action Procedure One.

372
00:25:17,082 --> 00:25:20,319
-You think I don't know that?
-I think you need reminding.

373
00:25:22,521 --> 00:25:23,689
Yeah.

374
00:25:25,257 --> 00:25:28,761
-Well, at least I'm good for something.
-Now and again.

375
00:25:29,528 --> 00:25:33,365
That's almost a compliment.
Things must be serious.

376
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:38,937
(STAMMERING) Sorry, sorry, but
Action One, that means evacuation, yeah?

377
00:25:39,038 --> 00:25:40,105
We're going home.

378
00:25:40,205 --> 00:25:42,408
This is Captain Brooke.
I'm declaring Action One.

379
00:25:42,508 --> 00:25:43,942
Repeat. To all crew members,

380
00:25:44,043 --> 00:25:46,278
this is Action One
with immediate effect.

381
00:25:46,378 --> 00:25:47,446
Evacuate the base.

382
00:25:47,546 --> 00:25:48,614
(ALARM BLARING)

383
00:25:48,714 --> 00:25:51,717
I'll store the central computer.
Mia, strip the cargo down to essentials.

384
00:25:51,817 --> 00:25:54,019
-Roman, on your feet.
-But we came all this way.

385
00:25:54,119 --> 00:25:55,287
Gadget-gadget.

386
00:25:56,121 --> 00:25:58,090
And you can kiss that robot goodbye.
It's too heavy.

387
00:25:58,190 --> 00:26:00,392
Now shove it in storage and hurry up.

388
00:26:00,492 --> 00:26:02,795
ADELAIDE ON RADIO: Stef ft what's
your estimate on shuttle viability?

389
00:26:02,895 --> 00:26:03,929
It's a nine-month flight.

390
00:26:04,029 --> 00:26:06,365
It'll take us at least three hours
to load up everything we need.

391
00:26:06,465 --> 00:26:10,235
You've got 20 minutes.
And give me a report on Andy and Tarak.

392
00:26:10,335 --> 00:26:12,004
Still in the Bio-dome tunnel.

393
00:26:12,104 --> 00:26:14,406
They're just standing there,
like they're waiting.

394
00:26:14,506 --> 00:26:17,576
Keep an eye on them.
And make that 20 minutes 15.

395
00:26:17,676 --> 00:26:20,312
Ed, line up the shuttle.
Go straight to ignition status.

396
00:26:20,412 --> 00:26:21,747
-Doing it now.
-But what about Maggie?

397
00:26:21,847 --> 00:26:24,016
She stays behind. We've got no way
to contain her on board.

398
00:26:24,116 --> 00:26:27,052
Close this place down. I want the power
directed to the shuttle.

399
00:26:27,553 --> 00:26:28,987
Of course, the only problem is...

400
00:26:29,088 --> 00:26:31,490
Thank you, Doctor. Your spacesuit
will be returned and good luck to you.

401
00:26:31,590 --> 00:26:33,092
The problem is this thing is clever.

402
00:26:33,192 --> 00:26:35,928
It didn't infect the bird or the insects
in the Bio-dome, it chose the humans.

403
00:26:36,028 --> 00:26:37,062
You were chosen.

404
00:26:37,162 --> 00:26:39,865
And I told you, Adelaide,
water can wait.

405
00:26:40,165 --> 00:26:42,034
Tarak changed straightaway,
but when Maggie was infected,

406
00:26:42,134 --> 00:26:46,705
it stayed hidden inside her, no doubt,
so it can infiltrate the Central dome.

407
00:26:46,972 --> 00:26:48,273
Which means...

408
00:26:48,373 --> 00:26:50,843
Any one of us could already be infected.

409
00:26:51,210 --> 00:26:55,280
-We've all been drinking the same water.
-And if you take that back to Earth...

410
00:26:56,315 --> 00:26:58,917
One drop, just one drop...

411
00:26:59,184 --> 00:27:01,620
But we're only presuming infection.

412
00:27:01,720 --> 00:27:05,491
If we can find out how this thing
got through, when it got through...

413
00:27:05,891 --> 00:27:09,628
Yuri, continue with Action One.
I'm going to inspect the ice field.

414
00:27:10,329 --> 00:27:12,631
Right. I should leave.

415
00:27:13,198 --> 00:27:14,933
Finally, I should leave.

416
00:27:15,334 --> 00:27:18,504
Yuri, me old mate,
no point in me seeing the ice field.

417
00:27:18,604 --> 00:27:21,440
No point at all. No.

418
00:27:25,010 --> 00:27:26,879
Adelaide!

419
00:27:32,184 --> 00:27:34,019
All I'm saying is bikes.

420
00:27:34,119 --> 00:27:36,488
Little, foldaway bikes.
Don't weigh a thing.

421
00:27:44,196 --> 00:27:45,531
I'm sorry.

422
00:28:09,388 --> 00:28:10,722
Even if she gets past the Medical dome,

423
00:28:10,822 --> 00:28:13,525
she'll never get past the Hardinger seal
at this end, right?

424
00:28:13,959 --> 00:28:15,661
So we keep saying.

425
00:28:19,198 --> 00:28:20,666
Camera's down.

426
00:28:21,466 --> 00:28:23,035
We've lost her.

427
00:28:31,877 --> 00:28:33,278
(SCREAMING)

428
00:28:53,665 --> 00:28:56,535
They tell legends of Mars from long ago

429
00:28:56,635 --> 00:28:59,905
of a fine and noble race
who built an empire out of snow.

430
00:29:00,405 --> 00:29:03,475
-The Ice Warriors.
-I haven't got time for stories.

431
00:29:03,575 --> 00:29:06,345
Perhaps they found something down there.

432
00:29:06,712 --> 00:29:09,147
Used their might and their wisdom
to freeze it.

433
00:29:09,248 --> 00:29:12,384
Doctor, we need to find any sort
of change in the water process.

434
00:29:12,484 --> 00:29:14,019
We've got to date the infection.

435
00:29:17,723 --> 00:29:20,025
COMPUTER: Access denied.

436
00:29:20,792 --> 00:29:25,163
You don't look like a coward,
but all you've wanted to do is leave.

437
00:29:27,232 --> 00:29:30,669
-You know so much about us.
-Well, you're famous.

438
00:29:31,303 --> 00:29:32,671
It's like you know more.

439
00:29:36,875 --> 00:29:40,746
This moment, this precise moment
in time, it's like...

440
00:29:42,147 --> 00:29:44,082
I mean, it's only a theory.
What do I know?

441
00:29:44,182 --> 00:29:48,920
But I think certain moments in time
are fixed.

442
00:29:50,455 --> 00:29:52,057
Tiny, precious moments.

443
00:29:52,157 --> 00:29:53,659
Everything else is in flux,
anything can happen,

444
00:29:53,759 --> 00:29:56,762
but those certain moments,
they have to stand.

445
00:29:58,263 --> 00:30:00,832
This base on Mars
with you, Adelaide Brooke,

446
00:30:00,932 --> 00:30:02,334
this is one vital moment.

447
00:30:02,434 --> 00:30:05,037
What happens here must always happen.

448
00:30:05,270 --> 00:30:06,772
Which is what?

449
00:30:07,906 --> 00:30:09,341
I don't know.

450
00:30:13,545 --> 00:30:16,081
I think something wonderful happens,

451
00:30:17,149 --> 00:30:20,719
something that started 50 years ago,
isn't that right?

452
00:30:23,155 --> 00:30:25,324
I've never told anyone that.

453
00:30:25,524 --> 00:30:27,426
You told your daughter.

454
00:30:28,427 --> 00:30:32,097
And, maybe, one day she tells a story
to her daughter

455
00:30:32,531 --> 00:30:36,435
of the day the Earth was stolen
and moved across the universe.

456
00:30:37,336 --> 00:30:38,670
And you...

457
00:30:41,373 --> 00:30:43,041
I saw the Daleks.

458
00:30:47,679 --> 00:30:49,147
We looked up,

459
00:30:50,349 --> 00:30:52,184
the sky had changed.

460
00:30:53,652 --> 00:30:56,221
Everyone was running and screaming.

461
00:30:57,456 --> 00:30:59,157
And my father took hold of me.

462
00:31:00,292 --> 00:31:02,861
Stay here. Don't move.

463
00:31:03,395 --> 00:31:06,031
I've got to go out.
I'm going to find your mother.

464
00:31:06,131 --> 00:31:09,000
But I'm coming back, I promise you.

465
00:31:09,801 --> 00:31:11,370
I'm coming back.

466
00:31:19,411 --> 00:31:21,747
ADELAIDE: I never saw him again.

467
00:31:23,415 --> 00:31:26,585
Nor my mother. They were never found.

468
00:31:30,689 --> 00:31:36,928
But, out on the streets,
there was panic and burning.

469
00:31:39,631 --> 00:31:41,466
I went to the window.

470
00:31:45,103 --> 00:31:48,306
And there, in the sky...

471
00:31:49,875 --> 00:31:51,543
I saw it Doctor.

472
00:31:53,478 --> 00:31:55,447
And it saw me.

473
00:31:56,415 --> 00:31:58,049
It stared at me.

474
00:31:58,750 --> 00:32:01,620
It looked right into me.

475
00:32:08,727 --> 00:32:10,095
And then...

476
00:32:23,208 --> 00:32:24,976
It simply went away.

477
00:32:25,944 --> 00:32:28,814
I knew, that night,

478
00:32:30,315 --> 00:32:32,350
I knew I would follow it.

479
00:32:33,185 --> 00:32:36,688
-But not for revenge.
-What would be the point of that?

480
00:32:38,990 --> 00:32:41,426
That's what makes you remarkable.

481
00:32:41,927 --> 00:32:44,429
And that's how you create history.

482
00:32:44,996 --> 00:32:47,866
-What do you mean?
-Imagine it, Adelaide.

483
00:32:49,534 --> 00:32:52,671
If you began a journey
that takes the human race

484
00:32:52,771 --> 00:32:56,508
all the way out to the stars.
It begins with you.

485
00:32:57,409 --> 00:33:00,412
And then your granddaughter,
you inspire her

486
00:33:00,912 --> 00:33:03,748
so that, in 30 years,
Susie Fontana Brooke

487
00:33:03,849 --> 00:33:07,819
is the pilot of the first
light-speed ship to Proxima Centauri.

488
00:33:14,259 --> 00:33:16,027
And then everywhere.

489
00:33:16,294 --> 00:33:19,664
With her children and
her children's children forging the way

490
00:33:19,764 --> 00:33:23,201
to the Dragon Star,
the Celestial Belt of the Winter Queen,

491
00:33:23,301 --> 00:33:25,704
map of the Water Snake Wormholes.

492
00:33:26,872 --> 00:33:30,008
One day, a Brooke will even fall in love
with a Tandonian prince

493
00:33:30,108 --> 00:33:32,310
and that's the start of
a whole new species.

494
00:33:32,410 --> 00:33:35,080
But everything starts with you,
Adelaide.

495
00:33:35,180 --> 00:33:39,050
From 50 years ago to right here, today.

496
00:33:41,453 --> 00:33:42,754
Imagine.

497
00:33:43,588 --> 00:33:47,125
Who are you?
Why are you telling me this?

498
00:33:48,860 --> 00:33:52,230
Doctor, why tell me?

499
00:33:54,065 --> 00:33:55,767
As consolation.

500
00:33:58,036 --> 00:33:59,037
(BEEPING)

501
00:34:00,605 --> 00:34:03,508
Andy Stone. He logged on yesterday.

502
00:34:05,777 --> 00:34:09,614
Maintenance log 2120, November, 20589.

503
00:34:10,048 --> 00:34:13,251
Number three water filter's bust.
And guess what?

504
00:34:13,385 --> 00:34:16,555
The spares they sent don't fit.
What a surprise.

505
00:34:16,755 --> 00:34:18,223
Over and out.

506
00:34:18,790 --> 00:34:20,091
A filter.

507
00:34:20,926 --> 00:34:23,495
One tiny little filter
and then the flood.

508
00:34:23,595 --> 00:34:25,830
But that means the infection
arrived today,

509
00:34:25,931 --> 00:34:29,668
and the water's only cycled out
of the Bio-dome after a week.

510
00:34:29,768 --> 00:34:32,804
The rest of us can't be infected.
We can leave.

511
00:34:33,171 --> 00:34:36,141
Ed, we're clean. How are we doing?

512
00:34:36,608 --> 00:34:38,009
Shuttle's active, stage one.

513
00:34:44,382 --> 00:34:46,351
I haven't got time to
convey the protein packs.

514
00:34:46,451 --> 00:34:48,720
If you want food, you're going to
have to carry it by hand.

515
00:34:48,820 --> 00:34:50,889
Start loading. Right now.

516
00:35:03,335 --> 00:35:05,904
-You were right, Doctor.
-What about?

517
00:35:06,204 --> 00:35:07,372
Bikes.

518
00:35:07,539 --> 00:35:08,607
(LAUGHING)

519
00:35:10,675 --> 00:35:14,079
Now, get to your ship.
I'm saving my people, you save yourself.

520
00:35:14,179 --> 00:35:18,350
I know what this moment is.
It's the moment we escape. Now get out.

521
00:35:22,587 --> 00:35:23,888
-Come on!
-How many do we need?

522
00:35:28,426 --> 00:35:31,730
(CREW ISSUING INSTRUCTIONS)

523
00:35:33,965 --> 00:35:35,333
ADELAIDE: Roman, what about you?

524
00:35:35,433 --> 00:35:38,036
Protein packs, 30 to 36.

525
00:35:38,136 --> 00:35:39,904
ED: Hurry up, Roman!

526
00:35:41,740 --> 00:35:43,008
I'm on it!

527
00:35:43,808 --> 00:35:45,377
(BEEPING)

528
00:35:49,314 --> 00:35:51,650
Stef ft, ditch the central containers.
We don't need them.

529
00:35:51,750 --> 00:35:54,653
Units 41, 42 and 43.

530
00:35:54,753 --> 00:35:56,988
No, wait, 41 is here.
I'll swap them around.

531
00:35:57,355 --> 00:35:58,456
(BEEPING)

532
00:36:00,458 --> 00:36:02,160
Roman, try to condense
the oxygen membranes.

533
00:36:02,260 --> 00:36:04,229
We can lose ten pounds. Faster! Come on!

534
00:36:04,329 --> 00:36:08,233
-Ed, how's the fuel jets?
-Cooling down in about 30 seconds.

535
00:36:12,470 --> 00:36:14,305
(BEEPING)

536
00:36:22,247 --> 00:36:24,649
(SENSORS BEEPING)

537
00:36:24,749 --> 00:36:26,251
What the hell is that noise?

538
00:36:26,351 --> 00:36:28,353
Mia, you lot, shut up.

539
00:36:28,453 --> 00:36:29,854
(SENSORS CONTINUE BEEPING)

540
00:36:29,954 --> 00:36:32,357
It's the module sensors.
Exterior as well.

541
00:36:32,457 --> 00:36:34,926
The cameras are down, but there's
pressure on top of the module.

542
00:36:35,026 --> 00:36:37,395
Two signals right above us.

543
00:36:37,862 --> 00:36:42,267
That means...they're on the roof?

544
00:36:55,647 --> 00:36:58,917
-How did they get inside the dome?
-They used the maintenance shafts.

545
00:36:59,017 --> 00:37:01,252
But the shaft's open
and they haven't got spacesuits.

546
00:37:01,352 --> 00:37:03,121
-ED: They breathe water.
-They'd freeze.

547
00:37:03,221 --> 00:37:05,490
YURI: They've got that internal fission.

548
00:37:05,590 --> 00:37:07,759
MIA: Are we safe?
They can't get through, can they?

549
00:37:07,859 --> 00:37:10,428
(CEILING CREAKING)

550
00:37:13,131 --> 00:37:14,566
Can they?

551
00:37:17,368 --> 00:37:20,939
-This place is airtight.
-Can it get through? Ed?

552
00:37:22,373 --> 00:37:24,008
-Can it get through?
-I don't know.

553
00:37:24,109 --> 00:37:26,644
Water itself isn't motile,
but it has some sort of resistance.

554
00:37:26,745 --> 00:37:31,549
Everyone, listen to me. That's
10 feet of steel combination up there.

555
00:37:31,649 --> 00:37:34,052
We need all the protein packs
or we're going to starve.

556
00:37:34,152 --> 00:37:35,754
Now, keep working.

557
00:37:35,854 --> 00:37:38,656
Roman, watch the ceiling.
Ed, get to the shuttle, fire it up.

558
00:37:38,757 --> 00:37:40,358
I can carry more than this lot, Captain.

559
00:37:40,458 --> 00:37:43,128
-That's an order.
-Captain.

560
00:38:56,534 --> 00:39:00,638
COMPUTER: Access denied. Access denied.

561
00:39:02,707 --> 00:39:04,175
ADELAIDE ON MONITOR:
Tell me what happens.

562
00:39:04,275 --> 00:39:05,276
I don't know.

563
00:39:05,376 --> 00:39:07,278
Yes, you do. Now tell me.

564
00:39:07,378 --> 00:39:09,214
-You should be with the others.
-Tell me!

565
00:39:14,919 --> 00:39:18,857
I could ramp up the pressure
in that airlock and crush you.

566
00:39:19,390 --> 00:39:21,059
Except you won't.

567
00:39:21,159 --> 00:39:23,695
You could have shot Andy Stone,
but you didn't.

568
00:39:23,795 --> 00:39:25,630
I loved you for that.

569
00:39:28,399 --> 00:39:30,034
Imagine...

570
00:39:36,474 --> 00:39:38,543
Imagine you knew something.

571
00:39:43,448 --> 00:39:47,018
Imagine you found yourself somewhere,
I don't know, Pompeii.

572
00:39:47,118 --> 00:39:48,286
Imagine you were in Pompeii.

573
00:39:48,386 --> 00:39:50,121
What the hell has that
got to do with it?

574
00:39:50,221 --> 00:39:54,225
And you tried to save them,
but, in doing so, you make it happen.

575
00:39:58,496 --> 00:40:00,031
Anything I do

576
00:40:02,467 --> 00:40:04,335
just makes it happen.

577
00:40:05,904 --> 00:40:08,239
Captain, we need you right now.

578
00:40:11,943 --> 00:40:13,511
ADELAIDE: I'm still here.

579
00:40:20,251 --> 00:40:22,253
You're taking Action One.

580
00:40:24,956 --> 00:40:28,660
There are four more standard
action procedures and Action Five is...

581
00:40:29,894 --> 00:40:31,329
Detonation.

582
00:40:31,429 --> 00:40:33,097
The final option.

583
00:40:34,666 --> 00:40:37,602
The nuclear device at the heart
of the Central dome.

584
00:40:37,702 --> 00:40:42,173
Today, on the 21st of November, 2058,

585
00:40:42,707 --> 00:40:45,610
Captain Brooke activates that device,

586
00:40:45,710 --> 00:40:48,913
taking the base
and all her crew members with her.

587
00:40:50,782 --> 00:40:52,750
No one ever knows why.

588
00:40:55,453 --> 00:40:57,555
But you were saving Earth.

589
00:40:57,956 --> 00:41:00,692
That's what inspires your granddaughter.

590
00:41:01,759 --> 00:41:04,529
She takes your people out
into the galaxy

591
00:41:05,463 --> 00:41:08,333
because you die on Mars.

592
00:41:11,869 --> 00:41:13,338
You die today.

593
00:41:17,275 --> 00:41:19,077
She flies out there

594
00:41:21,913 --> 00:41:24,182
like she's trying to meet you.

595
00:41:26,651 --> 00:41:28,119
I won't die.

596
00:41:29,587 --> 00:41:30,989
I will not.

597
00:41:31,422 --> 00:41:33,891
But your death creates the future.

598
00:41:37,495 --> 00:41:38,796
Help me.

599
00:41:41,032 --> 00:41:43,534
Why won't you help, Doctor,
if you know all of this?

600
00:41:43,634 --> 00:41:45,770
-Why can't you change it?
-I can't.

601
00:41:45,870 --> 00:41:48,072
-Why can't you find a way? Tell me.
-Adelaide, I swear, I can't.

602
00:41:48,172 --> 00:41:50,174
I'm sorry, but I can't.

603
00:41:50,408 --> 00:41:53,878
Sometimes I can, sometimes I do.
Most times, I can save someone.

604
00:41:53,978 --> 00:41:56,848
Or anyone. But not you.

605
00:41:58,783 --> 00:42:03,154
You wondered all your life why that
Dalek spared you. I think it knew.

606
00:42:03,821 --> 00:42:07,458
Your death is fixed in time forever.

607
00:42:09,560 --> 00:42:11,195
And that's right.

608
00:42:11,662 --> 00:42:13,798
-You'll die here, too?
-No.

609
00:42:14,999 --> 00:42:16,968
What's going to save you?

610
00:42:17,702 --> 00:42:19,704
Captain Adelaide Brooke.

611
00:42:27,779 --> 00:42:29,313
(AIR WHOOSHING)

612
00:42:33,618 --> 00:42:34,919
Damn you.

613
00:42:35,119 --> 00:42:36,788
(DOOR OPENING)

614
00:42:37,288 --> 00:42:39,357
Water! We've got water!

615
00:42:39,457 --> 00:42:42,326
MIA: Captain! Get back! Get back!
Captain!

616
00:42:42,427 --> 00:42:44,729
Don't touch it, Roman!
Don't let it touch you!

617
00:42:44,829 --> 00:42:45,830
ADELAIDE: Get back!

618
00:42:45,930 --> 00:42:48,366
Everyone, we're abandoning this section.
Get to the shuttle.

619
00:42:48,466 --> 00:42:51,135
Yuri, lead the way.
Section B corridor, now.

620
00:42:53,538 --> 00:42:55,940
STEFFI: Get that. And that.

621
00:42:57,275 --> 00:42:58,543
Close it!

622
00:42:58,943 --> 00:43:00,878
STEFFI: Yuri, did that water touch you?

623
00:43:00,978 --> 00:43:03,014
-I'm safe.
-Did it touch you? Yuri?

624
00:43:03,114 --> 00:43:05,216
-Did that water touch you?
-I'm clean, I'm dry.

625
00:43:05,316 --> 00:43:07,885
Everyone, Section B is out.
Listen to me.

626
00:43:07,985 --> 00:43:10,455
Take every pack that you can.
We'll go round.

627
00:43:10,555 --> 00:43:12,457
We'll make our way out
through Section F.

628
00:43:15,426 --> 00:43:17,762
STEFFI: Transferring authorisation,
Section F.

629
00:43:17,862 --> 00:43:20,465
Mia, you take the red line stock.
And hurry up!

630
00:43:20,531 --> 00:43:21,899
(CLANGING)

631
00:43:27,071 --> 00:43:28,706
YURI: Stef ft! Go!

632
00:43:29,574 --> 00:43:31,008
MIA: Stef ft, get back!

633
00:43:31,109 --> 00:43:32,443
-Get back!
-Stef ft, keep back!

634
00:43:32,543 --> 00:43:35,179
YURI: Get back!
ADELAIDE: Stef ft!

635
00:43:35,279 --> 00:43:36,881
YURI: Just get back! Stef ft!
MIA: Get back!

636
00:43:36,981 --> 00:43:39,917
-Get back! Hurry!
-MIA: You'll be safer there!

637
00:43:40,017 --> 00:43:42,787
ROMAN: Just shut the door!
Close the door!

638
00:43:44,355 --> 00:43:47,792
Stef ft, we'll come get you, okay?
We'll come get you!

639
00:43:49,227 --> 00:43:50,394
(EXCLAIMING)

640
00:43:50,495 --> 00:43:52,497
-Stef ft!
-Captain!

641
00:43:52,797 --> 00:43:56,801
We'll open the access panel.
We'll get you out through the back.

642
00:43:57,702 --> 00:43:59,137
Get her out! Move it!

643
00:43:59,237 --> 00:44:00,838
(STEFFI SCREAMS)

644
00:44:01,372 --> 00:44:03,241
Captain, it's inside!

645
00:44:06,110 --> 00:44:09,247
ROMAN: Stef ft!
MIA: Stef ft, get back. Stef ft!

646
00:44:09,347 --> 00:44:12,250
ADELAIDE: We're coming, Stef ft. Hold on!

647
00:44:12,350 --> 00:44:15,019
ROMAN: The access panel's
fused, Captain.

648
00:44:15,119 --> 00:44:17,955
-We can't open it.
-YURI: We can't get through.

649
00:44:18,055 --> 00:44:20,191
STEFFI: Don't! Don't please!
YURI: 7here's nothing we can do.

650
00:44:20,291 --> 00:44:22,426
STEFFI: 7 can't move!

651
00:44:29,133 --> 00:44:31,435
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

652
00:44:42,680 --> 00:44:44,549
(SOBBING)

653
00:44:45,850 --> 00:44:48,052
(GIRL CONTNUES SPEAKING GERMAN
ON MONITOR)

654
00:44:51,422 --> 00:44:54,025
Stef ft, can you hear me?

655
00:44:57,295 --> 00:44:58,663
Oh, my God.

656
00:45:01,666 --> 00:45:04,535
(CHILD CONTINUES SPEAKING GERMAN
ON MONITOR)

657
00:45:06,437 --> 00:45:08,306
Out. Get out.

658
00:45:24,589 --> 00:45:26,624
Ed, we're going around the long way.
How are we doing?

659
00:45:27,758 --> 00:45:30,995
All systems online 100%.
Not a single delay.

660
00:45:31,095 --> 00:45:34,098
Don't you worry, Captain,
we are gonna fly.

661
00:45:37,468 --> 00:45:39,770
ADELAIDE: I need air in Section F,
right now.

662
00:45:39,870 --> 00:45:43,107
YURI: Locking chamber three.
Locking chamber four.

663
00:45:44,375 --> 00:45:49,213
ADELAIDE: Keep looking.
ROMAN: Gate 5 is open. Gate 6 is open.

664
00:45:49,981 --> 00:45:53,317
YURI: Quickly. Come on.
MIA: I've got 25 to 30 lockdown.

665
00:45:56,854 --> 00:46:00,157
-Roman, come on, with me.
-You better go.

666
00:46:00,424 --> 00:46:02,493
ADELAIDE: Don't just stand there, move.

667
00:46:02,593 --> 00:46:05,196
ROMAN: You'd really better
go without me.

668
00:46:05,296 --> 00:46:07,031
I'm sorry, Captain.

669
00:46:09,100 --> 00:46:10,401
One drop.

670
00:46:16,107 --> 00:46:19,777
Roman! Roman!

671
00:46:19,877 --> 00:46:21,412
Leave him. Come on.

672
00:46:22,913 --> 00:46:25,082
MIA: We can't just leave him!
YURI: Sorry. Come on!

673
00:46:25,182 --> 00:46:26,550
MIA: Left me go!
YURI: 7 can't let you go.

674
00:46:26,651 --> 00:46:28,519
MIA: (CRYING) Roman!

675
00:46:28,619 --> 00:46:29,987
YURI: I'm so sorry.

676
00:46:35,993 --> 00:46:37,395
(GROANING)

677
00:46:40,197 --> 00:46:43,100
-ED: Captain, the shuttle is down.
-What the hell do you mean?

678
00:46:43,200 --> 00:46:45,636
Compromised. It was Maggie.

679
00:46:45,736 --> 00:46:47,872
-ADELAIDE: Get out of there.
-Too late.

680
00:46:50,541 --> 00:46:54,378
And they want this ship to get to Earth.
Got no choice.

681
00:46:55,379 --> 00:46:57,515
(ED GROANING)

682
00:46:57,615 --> 00:46:59,350
Hated it Adelaide.

683
00:47:00,785 --> 00:47:03,220
(GROANING) This bloody job.

684
00:47:03,921 --> 00:47:05,990
You never gave me a chance.

685
00:47:09,193 --> 00:47:10,995
(BEEPING)

686
00:47:13,531 --> 00:47:15,633
You never could forgive me.

687
00:47:17,702 --> 00:47:19,470
See you later.

688
00:47:22,273 --> 00:47:23,641
(ALL SCREAMING)

689
00:47:38,055 --> 00:47:40,624
(AIR ESCAPING)

690
00:47:44,762 --> 00:47:47,231
We're losing oxygen!

691
00:47:47,998 --> 00:47:50,868
The hull is broken!

692
00:47:57,875 --> 00:48:01,879
DOCTOR: I'm not just a Time Lord,
I'm the last of the Time Lords.

693
00:48:07,184 --> 00:48:09,720
MAN: You'll never come back, Doctor.

694
00:48:10,788 --> 00:48:14,258
DOCTOR: I've got a TARDIS.
Same old life, last of the Time Lords.

695
00:48:14,425 --> 00:48:16,627
And they died, took it all with them.

696
00:48:16,994 --> 00:48:20,898
The walls of reality closed,
the worlds were sealed, gone forever.

697
00:48:21,298 --> 00:48:24,402
And the Time Lords kept their eye
on everything. And it's gone now.

698
00:48:24,502 --> 00:48:27,972
But they died, the Time Lords.
All of them, they died.

699
00:48:28,339 --> 00:48:30,674
I'm the last of the Time Lords.

700
00:48:31,375 --> 00:48:33,244
(ALARM BLARING)

701
00:48:42,253 --> 00:48:45,089
Mia, take this sealant and fix that rig.

702
00:48:45,189 --> 00:48:47,958
Yuri, open the emergency oxygen.

703
00:48:48,058 --> 00:48:50,361
Adelaide, don't just sit there.

704
00:48:55,199 --> 00:48:58,436
That's better.
The dome's still got integrity.

705
00:48:58,536 --> 00:49:00,538
It's 10 feet of steel combination
made in Liverpool.

706
00:49:00,638 --> 00:49:02,072
Magnificent workmanship.

707
00:49:02,173 --> 00:49:04,008
It can't be stopped. Don't die with us.

708
00:49:04,108 --> 00:49:05,643
No, because someone told me
just recently,

709
00:49:05,743 --> 00:49:07,044
they said I was going to die.

710
00:49:07,144 --> 00:49:09,713
They said he will knock four times
and I think I know what that means.

711
00:49:09,814 --> 00:49:11,682
And it doesn't mean
right here, right now.

712
00:49:11,782 --> 00:49:13,717
'Cause I don't hear anyone knocking,
do you?

713
00:49:13,818 --> 00:49:16,020
(BANGING ON DOOR)

714
00:49:18,022 --> 00:49:20,157
Three knocks is all you're getting.

715
00:49:20,758 --> 00:49:22,993
(SCREAMING)

716
00:49:23,861 --> 00:49:26,931
Water and electricity, bad mix.
Now then, what else have we got?

717
00:49:27,031 --> 00:49:28,399
But there's no way to fight them.

718
00:49:28,499 --> 00:49:31,235
Heat! They use water,
so we can use heat.

719
00:49:31,335 --> 00:49:33,437
Works against the Ice Warriors,
works against the flood.

720
00:49:33,537 --> 00:49:35,239
We'll ramp up the environment controls
and steam them!

721
00:49:35,339 --> 00:49:36,507
But you said we die.

722
00:49:36,574 --> 00:49:37,775
(THUDDING)

723
00:49:38,542 --> 00:49:40,177
For the future, for the human race.

724
00:49:40,277 --> 00:49:42,513
Yes, because there are laws.
There are laws of time.

725
00:49:42,613 --> 00:49:47,017
Once upon a time, there were people
in charge of those laws, but they died.

726
00:49:47,117 --> 00:49:50,254
They all died.
Do you know who that leaves? Me!

727
00:49:50,921 --> 00:49:53,958
It's taken me all these years to realise
the laws of time are mine

728
00:49:54,058 --> 00:49:55,526
and they will obey me!

729
00:49:55,626 --> 00:49:56,727
(GROANING)

730
00:49:56,827 --> 00:49:58,462
(ALARM BLARING)

731
00:50:01,632 --> 00:50:03,334
Environmental controls are down.

732
00:50:03,434 --> 00:50:05,903
Sorry, Doc, but it looks like
history's got other ideas.

733
00:50:06,003 --> 00:50:08,906
Not beaten yet. I'll go outside!

734
00:50:09,540 --> 00:50:11,075
Look at the heat regulator.

735
00:50:12,443 --> 00:50:13,744
Not beaten, not beaten!

736
00:50:13,844 --> 00:50:16,380
You've got spacesuits
in the next section!

737
00:50:20,317 --> 00:50:24,121
We're not just fighting the flood,
we're fighting time itself

738
00:50:24,221 --> 00:50:25,990
and I'm gonna win!

739
00:50:31,228 --> 00:50:33,697
(ROARING)

740
00:50:41,438 --> 00:50:43,407
Something is happening to the glacier.

741
00:50:43,507 --> 00:50:45,175
Think, think, think. What have we got?

742
00:50:45,276 --> 00:50:48,279
Not enough oxygen.
Protein packs, useless.

743
00:50:48,379 --> 00:50:51,582
Glacier, glacier...
Mints, minty, Monty, motto bene,

744
00:50:51,682 --> 00:50:52,783
bunny, bonny, bish, bash, bosh!

745
00:50:52,883 --> 00:50:54,018
Ahh! The room! The room! The room!

746
00:50:54,118 --> 00:50:56,754
Look at the room.
Section F... What's in Section F?

747
00:50:58,522 --> 00:51:01,759
-Anyone?
-Nothing. It's just storage.

748
00:51:02,092 --> 00:51:04,562
-Storing what?
-I don't know. The weather spikes,

749
00:51:04,662 --> 00:51:06,297
the robots, the atom clamps...

750
00:51:06,397 --> 00:51:08,432
Atom clamps, atom clamps!

751
00:51:08,566 --> 00:51:12,403
Who needs atom clamps?
I love a funny robot!

752
00:51:13,237 --> 00:51:14,738
Gadget-gadget.

753
00:51:14,905 --> 00:51:16,674
(CONTINUES ROARING)

754
00:51:21,579 --> 00:51:24,415
-You take that. Good boy.
-Gadget-gadget.

755
00:51:29,653 --> 00:51:32,122
-Off we go, then.
-Gadget-gadget.

756
00:51:41,398 --> 00:51:43,300
Come on! Come on!

757
00:51:50,741 --> 00:51:52,376
COMPUTER: Implementing
Captain's protocol.

758
00:51:52,476 --> 00:51:54,545
Adelaide, what are you doing?

759
00:51:54,645 --> 00:51:56,614
Oh, my God. Action Five.

760
00:51:56,714 --> 00:51:59,583
If I have to fight you as well,
then I will.

761
00:52:00,351 --> 00:52:02,920
COMPUTER: Nuclear device now active
and primed.

762
00:52:03,020 --> 00:52:05,789
Nuclear device now active and primed.

763
00:52:05,856 --> 00:52:07,858
Blast off!

764
00:52:08,158 --> 00:52:09,860
Gadget-gadget.

765
00:52:13,030 --> 00:52:15,165
Faster!

766
00:52:22,272 --> 00:52:24,108
(CONTINUES ROARING)

767
00:52:30,180 --> 00:52:32,383
(ALL ROARING)

768
00:52:50,801 --> 00:52:53,737
COMPUTER: Nuclear device
entering final process.

769
00:52:53,837 --> 00:52:54,905
(EXCLAIMING)

770
00:53:00,444 --> 00:53:01,512
Gadget-gadget.

771
00:53:07,785 --> 00:53:09,520
And we're in!

772
00:53:13,023 --> 00:53:14,324
(LAUGHING)

773
00:53:17,294 --> 00:53:19,630
(ALARM BLARING)

774
00:53:22,066 --> 00:53:23,333
(LAUGHING)

775
00:53:31,175 --> 00:53:32,776
Gadget-gadget.

776
00:53:32,943 --> 00:53:34,111
(EXCLAIMING)

777
00:54:58,629 --> 00:55:00,197
Isn't anyone going to thank me?

778
00:55:08,438 --> 00:55:11,475
He's lost his signal.
Doesn't know where he is.

779
00:55:12,910 --> 00:55:14,545
That's my house.

780
00:55:17,314 --> 00:55:18,982
Don't you get it?

781
00:55:19,817 --> 00:55:22,352
This is the 21st of November, 2059.

782
00:55:23,287 --> 00:55:25,522
Same day on Earth.

783
00:55:26,824 --> 00:55:29,059
And it's snowing. I love snow.

784
00:55:30,194 --> 00:55:31,962
What is that thing?

785
00:55:32,896 --> 00:55:38,068
It's bigger...
I mean, it's bigger on the inside.

786
00:55:39,436 --> 00:55:41,271
Who the hell are you?

787
00:55:49,446 --> 00:55:51,982
-Look after her.
-Yes, ma'am.

788
00:56:01,925 --> 00:56:04,828
-You saved us.
-Just think, though.

789
00:56:05,863 --> 00:56:10,000
Your daughter and your daughter's
daughter, you can see them again.

790
00:56:10,467 --> 00:56:13,503
-Family reunion.
-But I'm supposed to be dead.

791
00:56:14,071 --> 00:56:15,505
Not any more.

792
00:56:16,807 --> 00:56:19,576
But, Susie,

793
00:56:21,645 --> 00:56:23,347
my granddaughter,

794
00:56:24,381 --> 00:56:26,884
the person she's supposed to become

795
00:56:27,885 --> 00:56:29,486
might never exist now.

796
00:56:29,586 --> 00:56:32,856
Nah, Captain Adelaide
can inspire her face-to-face.

797
00:56:33,257 --> 00:56:34,958
Different details,
but the story's the same.

798
00:56:35,058 --> 00:56:36,860
You can't know that.

799
00:56:37,194 --> 00:56:42,766
And if my family changes,
the whole of history could change.

800
00:56:43,600 --> 00:56:47,704
The future of the human race.
No one should have that much power.

801
00:56:48,272 --> 00:56:49,439
Tough.

802
00:56:58,148 --> 00:57:00,384
You should have left us there.

803
00:57:00,984 --> 00:57:03,520
Adelaide, I've done this
sort of thing before,

804
00:57:03,620 --> 00:57:06,423
in small ways, saved some little people.

805
00:57:07,357 --> 00:57:10,360
But never someone as important as you.
Oh, I'm good.

806
00:57:10,460 --> 00:57:14,097
Little people? What, like Mia and Yuri?

807
00:57:14,197 --> 00:57:17,100
Who decides they're so unimportant? You?

808
00:57:18,035 --> 00:57:22,139
For a long time now, I thought I was
just a survivor, but I'm not.

809
00:57:23,006 --> 00:57:26,343
I'm the winner. That's who I am.

810
00:57:28,512 --> 00:57:30,547
The Time Lord Victorious.

811
00:57:34,952 --> 00:57:38,488
-And there's no one to stop you?
-No.

812
00:57:39,790 --> 00:57:43,961
This is wrong, Doctor.
I don't care who you are.

813
00:57:44,061 --> 00:57:46,697
The Time Lord Victorious is wrong.

814
00:57:46,863 --> 00:57:48,865
That's for me to decide.

815
00:57:52,202 --> 00:57:54,271
Now, you'd better get home.

816
00:57:54,738 --> 00:57:57,207
Oh, it's all locked up.
You've been away.

817
00:57:57,307 --> 00:57:59,309
Still, that's easy.

818
00:57:59,509 --> 00:58:00,677
(WHIRRING)

819
00:58:00,777 --> 00:58:02,579
(DOOR UNLOCKING)

820
00:58:05,248 --> 00:58:06,616
All yours.

821
00:58:08,618 --> 00:58:10,887
Is there nothing you can't do?

822
00:58:11,621 --> 00:58:13,056
Not any more.

823
00:58:48,291 --> 00:58:50,293
(GUNSHOT)

824
00:59:27,464 --> 00:59:29,699
ADELAIDE: I don't care who you are.

825
00:59:29,800 --> 00:59:32,235
The Time Lord Victorious is wrong.

826
00:59:44,448 --> 00:59:46,149
I've gone too far.

827
00:59:55,425 --> 00:59:59,763
Is this it? My death?

828
01:00:04,568 --> 01:00:05,969
Is it time?

829
01:00:46,476 --> 01:00:47,577
No.

830
01:00:52,782 --> 01:00:54,918
(LAUGHING)

831
01:00:57,687 --> 01:01:00,390
Every night, Doctor, we have bad dreams.

832
01:01:00,957 --> 01:01:04,261
But I was told he will knock four times.

833
01:01:04,361 --> 01:01:07,230
MAN: Because a shadow is
falling over creation.

834
01:01:07,330 --> 01:01:09,866
Something vast is stirring in the dark.

835
01:01:09,966 --> 01:01:11,601
I'm going to die.

836
01:01:16,673 --> 01:01:19,075
My name is the Master.

837
01:01:20,210 --> 01:01:22,345
MAN: The darkness heralds
only one thing...

838
01:01:22,445 --> 01:01:23,480
(LAUGHING)

839
01:01:23,980 --> 01:01:26,249
The end of time itself.

